EDR-0001

Date: July 14, 2026

Status: Accepted

Category: Audio

Decision

Project Disc will not include built-in speakers.

Context

The original concept considered integrated speakers.

After evaluating the tradeoffs, it was determined that built-in speakers would conflict with the project's goals of high-fidelity audio, durability, repairability, and efficient use of internal space.

Alternatives Considered
Mono speaker
Stereo speakers
Removable speaker module
No speakers
Pros
More room for battery
More room for DAC and audio circuitry
Better thermal layout
Lower power consumption
Cleaner internal design
Better audio quality through headphones and external systems
Cons
Cannot play audio without external equipment
Consequences

Project Disc becomes a dedicated personal listening device.

Future docking accessories may provide speaker functionality.

EDR-0002

Category: Mechanical

Decision

Project Disc shall prioritize durability over minimum thickness.

Context

Many modern electronics achieve thinness by sacrificing structural strength.

Project Disc aims to feel like a durable tool rather than a fragile gadget.

Decision

The enclosure should prioritize:

Structural rigidity
Impact resistance
Long-term reliability

Minor increases in thickness are acceptable when they improve durability or repairability.

EDR-0003

Category: Product Philosophy

Decision

Project Disc is a modular ecosystem rather than a single product.

Consequences

Every software module should be reusable.

Every future device should share:

UI
Communication protocol
Design language
Documentation standards
EDR-0004

Category: Repairability

Decision

Glue shall not be used for serviceable components unless there is no practical alternative.

Components Covered
Display
Battery
Main board
Buttons
Rotary encoder
Exceptions

Display laminations, battery cells, and other manufacturing processes that require adhesives may remain as supplied by the manufacturer.

